      <h2>CRAFTS</h2>
      <h3>1.AIPAN ART:</h3>
      <p>Aipan art, a traditional folk art of Uttarakhand, has been practiced for centuries, primarily by women, to mark religious and cultural events. It is believed to have originated in the hills of Garhwal and Kumaon, with designs inspired by nature, deities, and spiritual symbols. The art is used to decorate floors and walls of homes, particularly during festivals, weddings, and religious ceremonies. Aipan patterns are drawn using rice paste and are believed to bring prosperity, protection, and divine blessings to the household. Over time, Aipan evolved, incorporating geometric patterns, floral motifs, and animal figures. This intricate art form has been passed down through generations, with efforts being made to preserve it amidst modernity.</p>
     <img src="aipan.png">
     <h3>2.WOOD CARVING:</h3>
     <p>Wood carving in Uttarakhand has a long history, deeply rooted in the region's cultural and religious practices. The art form dates back to the 14th century when skilled artisans began carving intricate designs for temples, household items, and furniture. Carved wooden idols, doors, windows, and decorative pieces often feature motifs inspired by nature, mythology, and local traditions. The use of locally available wood, such as deodar and pine, made the craft both practical and symbolic. Wood carving became an integral part of temple architecture, with notable examples found in the ancient temples of Bageshwar and Almora. Today, the tradition continues, with artisans using both traditional techniques and modern designs to keep the craft alive.</p>
    <img src="wood.png">
     <h3>3.RINGAL HANDICRAFT</h3>
     <p>Ringal handicrafts have a long tradition in Uttarakhand, originating from the use of the Ringal plant, a bamboo-like grass found in the hilly regions. The craft dates back centuries, with locals using Ringal to create practical and decorative items like baskets, mats, and household utensils. This sustainable material is lightweight yet strong, making it ideal for crafting daily-use objects. Ringal weaving is especially prominent in the Kumaon and Garhwal regions, where artisans incorporate intricate designs passed down through generations. Over time, the craft evolved to include colorful patterns and functional items, such as containers and furniture. Today, Ringal handicrafts continue to be a symbol of Uttarakhand’s rural craftsmanship, with efforts made to promote and preserve this unique tradition.</p>
    <img src="ringal.png">
     <h3>4.WOOLEN HANDICRAFT</h3>
     <p>Woolen handicrafts in Uttarakhand have a rich history, shaped by the region’s cold climate and the availability of high-quality wool from local sheep and goats. The tradition of woolen weaving dates back centuries, with the people of Uttarakhand creating shawls, rugs, blankets, and garments to keep warm in the harsh winters. The craft flourished in the hill regions of Garhwal and Kumaon, where skilled artisans developed intricate handwoven patterns, including the famous "Kullu shawl." The woolen textiles were traditionally dyed using natural colors derived from local plants and minerals. Woolen handicrafts played an important role in the local economy, both for domestic use and trade. Today, these handcrafted woolen products remain a vital part of Uttarakhand’s cultural heritage and are cherished for their warmth, durability, and beauty.</p>
    <img src="woolen.png">
     <h3>5.STONE CARVING</h3>
     <p>Stone carving in Uttarakhand has ancient roots, with its origins traced back to the early centuries when local artisans began crafting idols and sculptures for temples and religious shrines. The region’s abundant availability of soft stones like sandstone and slate made it an ideal medium for carving. The craft became highly refined during the 8th and 9th centuries, particularly with the construction of temples, where stone carvings depicted gods, goddesses, and mythological scenes. Stone carving was also used to create architectural features, such as columns, arches, and door frames. Over time, the craft evolved, incorporating intricate patterns and regional motifs. Today, stone carving continues to be an important art form in Uttarakhand, with many temples and monuments showcasing the exquisite craftsmanship of local artisans</p>
