        <h3>FOLK DANCERS</h3>
        <h4>CHHOLIYA DANCE</h4>
        <p>Chholiya is a traditional folk dance from Uttarakhand, typically performed during wedding ceremonies and festive occasions. The dance is characterized by vigorous, energetic movements and is performed by both men and women, who wear traditional attire and wield swords, adding a martial element to the performance. The dancers move in a circle while chanting folk songs, symbolizing the celebration of life and prosperity. Chholiya's energetic footwork and rhythmic beats are accompanied by drums, providing a lively and festive atmosphere. This dance form reflects the cultural heritage of the Kumaon and Garhwal regions of Uttarakhand. It has become a symbol of the region’s martial traditions and vibrant celebrations.</p>
      <img src="chholiya.png">
        <h4>LANGVIR NRITYA</h4>
        <p>Langvir Nritya is a folk dance from the state of Himachal Pradesh, specifically associated with the Kullu region. The dance is performed during the annual Dussehra festival, where dancers, dressed in vibrant traditional attire, perform a rhythmic and graceful dance, symbolizing devotion and joy. Langvir Nritya involves rapid footwork and energetic movements that are accompanied by the beats of local drums and other traditional instruments. The dance is often performed by men who dance in a circle or line, displaying strength and unity. It is also known for its vibrant and colorful costumes, which include traditional hats and cloaks. This dance form holds great cultural significance, as it is a way to honor the local gods and goddesses.</p>
