        <h2>PAINTINGS</h2>
        <h3>MALLA AND KUMAONI</h3>
        <p>Malla and Kumaoni paintings are traditional art forms from the Kumaon region of Uttarakhand. These paintings are known for their vivid colors, intricate detailing, and depiction of religious themes, such as scenes from Hindu mythology. The style is characterized by the use of natural colors and a unique blend of Rajput and Pahari traditions. Artists use fine brushwork to create images of deities, animals, and landscapes. The art form reflects the cultural and spiritual life of the region. Kumaoni art is an essential part of the region's heritage, often seen in temples and homes.</p>
      <img src="malla.png"> 
        <h3>WARLI ART</h3>
        <p>Warli art is a tribal folk painting form that originates from the Warli tribes of Maharashtra. The paintings are created using white pigment made from rice paste on mud walls, primarily depicting daily life, nature, and animals. Warli art is famous for its geometric patterns, with circles, triangles, and squares symbolizing different elements of life. The art often represents a harmonious relationship between humans, animals, and nature, reflecting the tribe’s deep connection to the natural world. It is characterized by simplicity and minimalistic yet powerful visual storytelling. Warli paintings are gaining recognition globally for their unique aesthetic.</p>
      <img src="warli.png">
        <h3>MINIATURE PAINTING</h3>
        <p>Miniature paintings are small-scale works of art, often rich in detail and vibrant in color. Originating in India during the Mughal, Rajput, and Pahari dynasties, these paintings depict court scenes, royal portraits, religious themes, and historical events. The art form is known for its intricate brushwork, fine detailing, and the use of natural colors and gold leaf. Miniatures are typically painted on materials like paper, ivory, and cloth. They were often created as manuscripts or album pages and are considered a luxurious art form. Indian miniature painting styles vary across regions, such as Mughal, Rajput, Pahari, and Deccan.</p>
      <img src="mini.png">
        <h3>CHANDINI RAJPUT</h3>
        <p>Chandini Rajput is an artist known for her contributions to traditional Rajput painting. While her work combines modern techniques with classical Rajput styles, it focuses on portraying the culture and grandeur of the Rajputana kingdom. Rajput paintings are known for their elaborate depictions of royal life, battle scenes, and the elegance of Rajasthan’s palaces and courts. Chandini’s art often features bold colors, intricate detailing, and a strong sense of narrative. She is known for preserving and reviving traditional Rajput painting techniques in contemporary contexts, adding depth and relevance to the art form.</p>
