        <h2>TEXTIAL ARTS</h2>
        <h3>PASHMINA WOOL WEAVING</h3>
        <p>Pashmina wool weaving is a centuries-old tradition from Kashmir, known for producing luxurious and fine fabrics. The wool is derived from the undercoat of the Pashmina goat, which is native to the Himalayas. The weaving process involves hand-spinning the wool into fine threads, which are then woven into delicate, soft, and warm shawls, stoles, and scarves. The intricate weaving techniques produce a lightweight yet highly insulating fabric. Pashmina textiles are highly prized for their softness, warmth, and durability. This form of weaving is passed down through generations and is integral to the cultural heritage of Kashmir.</p>
      <img src="pashmina.png">
        <h3>KUMAI WOOLEN FABRIC</h3>
        <p>Kumai woolen fabric is a traditional textile craft from the Kumaon region of Uttarakhand. The wool used in Kumai weaving comes from local sheep, and the fabric is hand-woven using traditional techniques that date back centuries. Kumai fabric is known for its warm, dense texture, making it ideal for cold climates. The weaving involves both geometric patterns and intricate motifs that reflect the region’s culture and natural surroundings. This textile is used to make woolen shawls, blankets, and clothing. Kumai woolen fabric plays a vital role in the local economy and is an essential part of Uttarakhand's textile heritage.</p>
      <img src="kumai.png">
        <h3>DHAMAN WEAVING</h3>
        <p>Dhaman weaving is a traditional weaving technique from the Garhwal region of Uttarakhand. It is mainly used to create woolen fabrics and is recognized for its durability and warmth. The process involves using wool spun by hand, and the woven textiles often feature bold, geometric patterns. Dhaman fabric is used in making blankets, rugs, and shawls, and it is known for its rugged yet comfortable texture. The weaving is typically done using a traditional loom, which allows for precision and intricate designs. This textile craft is an essential part of the cultural heritage of Garhwal, reflecting the region’s unique lifestyle and environment.</p>
      <img src="dhaman.png">
        <h3>AARI WORK EMBROIDARY</h3>
        <p>Aari work is a type of embroidery that involves using a hook (aari) to stitch intricate patterns onto fabric. This form of hand embroidery is commonly used in the making of traditional garments such as sarees, dupattas, and shawls. It is known for its fine detailing, which often includes floral, paisley, and geometric motifs. The threadwork in aari embroidery is delicate yet bold, often incorporating gold or silver threads to add a regal touch. This form of embroidery is popular in regions like Kashmir, Uttar Pradesh, and Gujarat, where it is used to embellish fabrics for both everyday wear and ceremonial occasions. Aari work is prized for its craftsmanship and the skill required to produce such detailed, artistic designs.</p>
